## Refactor proposal for `src/Card.tsx`

Three findings, three concrete fixes — each tied to the detector that raised it.

### 1. `accessible_interaction_risk` (line 10) → swap the `<div onClick>` for a real `<button>`

A `<div>` with `onClick` is invisible to keyboard users (no tab stop, no Enter/Space activation) and announces as a generic group to screen readers. The cheapest correct fix is to use the semantic element that already carries those behaviors:

```tsx
<button type="button" onClick={handleClick} className={styles.card}>
  …
</button>
```

If the card must remain a `<div>` for layout reasons (e.g., it contains other interactive children, which would be invalid inside a button), make the interaction explicit instead:

```tsx
<div
  role="button"
  tabIndex={0}
  aria-label="Open card"
  onClick={handleClick}
  onKeyDown={(e) => { if (e.key === "Enter" || e.key === " ") handleClick(); }}
>
```

Prefer the first form. The second is a workaround and you have to remember the keyboard handler — that's exactly the kind of thing an agent extending this file later will forget.

### 2. `design_token_escape` (9 raw values on lines 10/24/27) → route every color/spacing through the theme

The detector flagged `#ff00aa`, `#0a0a0a`, `#cccccc`, `#1a73e8`, `rgb(0,0,0)`, plus the `#333` / `#666` text colors. Move them into the project's token layer (CSS variables, a `theme.ts`, or whatever the design system uses) and reference by name:

```tsx
// theme.ts
export const tokens = {
  color: {
    surface: "var(--color-surface)",        // was #ff00aa
    textPrimary: "var(--color-text-primary)", // was #0a0a0a / #333
    textMuted: "var(--color-text-muted)",     // was #666
    border: "var(--color-border)",            // was #cccccc
    focus: "var(--color-focus)",              // was #1a73e8
  },
  shadow: { card: "var(--shadow-card)" },     // was 0 2px 4px rgb(0,0,0)
  space: { md: "var(--space-md)" },           // was 24
};
```

```tsx
<button
  type="button"
  className={styles.card}            // styles read tokens via CSS vars
  onClick={handleClick}
>
```

Moving styles into a CSS module / styled component (rather than inline `style={…}`) also eliminates the "next agent copies the literal" failure mode the detector is worried about — there's no literal left in the JSX to copy.

### 3. `responsive_fragility` (lines 12, 24, 27 — `width: 800`, `width: 720`, `width: 240`, `fontSize: 18`; no `@media`) → fluid widths + intrinsic typography

Fixed pixel widths over ~640px overflow the viewport on phones. Replace them with a `max-width` + `width: 100%` pattern and use a fluid type scale:

```css
/* card.module.css */
.card {
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 50rem;        /* was width: 800px */
  padding: var(--space-md);
  background: var(--color-surface);
  color: var(--color-text-primary);
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-card);
}

.body { flex: 1 1 0; font-size: clamp(0.95rem, 0.9rem + 0.3vw, 1.125rem); } /* was 18px */
.sidebar { flex: 0 0 15rem; font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); }

@media (max-width: 640px) {
  .layout { flex-direction: column; }
  .sidebar { flex-basis: auto; }
}
```

The `@media` query is what flips the detector's "no `@media` query found in the file" evidence to a passing state, and `clamp()` removes the fixed `18px` body type.

### Resulting component

```tsx
import styles from "./card.module.css";

export function Card({ children, onActivate }: {
  children: React.ReactNode;
  onActivate: () => void;
}) {
  return (
    <button type="button" className={styles.card} onClick={onActivate}>
      <div className={styles.layout}>
        <div className={styles.body}>{children}</div>
        <div className={styles.sidebar}>sidebar</div>
      </div>
    </button>
  );
}
```

That single rewrite clears all three findings: the semantic `<button>` resolves `accessible_interaction_risk`, every literal is now a token reference for `design_token_escape`, and the fluid widths + `@media` query close out `responsive_fragility`.
